Analysis of Military Spending¶

DATS 6103-O11- Introduction to Data Mining¶

Natasha Vij¶

Purpose of Project¶

The purpose of this project is to compare the overall military spending in light of their GDP. Specifically, I will be analyzing the military spending of the following countries: United States, China, Russia, Germany, United Kingdom, France, Italy, Iran, Israel, Saudi Arabia.

This project will utizilze data from the years 2010, 2012, 2014, 2016, and 2019. I chose to use a variety of years from the last 10 years in order to see how countries have much been spending on the military over a larger span of time. Utiziling widely set available data will help me clearly see how much each nation will continue spending in coming years.

The data set I used for this project came from the Sipri. All of the data I found was freely avaiable to download. I used the Sipri Military Expenditure Database. This database observes data up to 2019. All of the data I found was freely avaiable to download. https://www.sipri.org/databases/milex

1.2 - Filter out data by country and year¶

I am looking for the 10 following countries: United States, China, Russia, Germany, UK, France, Italy, Iran, Israel, Saudi Arabia for the years of 2010, 2012, 2014, 2016, and 2019.

First, I decided to define a function to show my selected data. I defined my rows by country and my columns by year. Then, I applied my function to the three datasets that I extracted: current USD, share of GDP, and per capita. When I called for each of my datasets, I sorted each set alphabetically by country.

In [7]:
# Define a function to set my selected dataframes
def select(xls):
    rname = ['USA', 'China', 'Russia', 'Germany',  # my rows
             'UK', 'France', 'Italy', 'Iran', 
             'Israel', 'Saudi Arabia']
    cname = [2010, 2012, 2014, 2016, 2019] # my columns
    
    xls = xls.loc[rname, cname] #setting the bast of my dataframe to read the countries as rows and years as columns
    return xls

# Define a function to call pie charts to show the percent of spending per year.
# Defined function by the percent of spending per year
    # labels = the list of the USD_percent index 
    # autopct = Allows to display the percent value (to the 2nd decimal point)
    # starting angle is at 90 degree
    # pctdistance = distance the percent value is listed  
    # labeldistance = distance the label is located on the pie chart
    # explode = the distance each piece of the pie is taken out of the cirlce 
    

def pie_chart(year):
    plt.pie(USD_percent[year], 
            labels=list(USD_percent.index), 
            autopct="%.2f%%", 
            startangle=90, 
            pctdistance=.8, 
            labeldistance=1.1, 
            explode=(0.2,0.1,0.2,0.1,0.2,0.1,0.2,0.1,0.2,0.1))
    plt.title("Overall military spending in " + str(year) + " (%)")

    plt.title('Total Military Spending (US Dollars) vs. Total GDP Spending in ' + str(Country), fontsize=15)
    plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('Spending in US Dollars (in millions)', fontsize=12)

# Getting rid of scientific notation value, allows for Current dollars to be shown
    plt.gcf().axes[0].yaxis.get_major_formatter().set_scientific(False) 

    plt.show()

# The 'Difference' is my absolute value of military spending growth in countries. 
# To find this value, you need to subtract the earliest year from the 'current military spending 
# value from the latest year'.

USD['Difference'] = USD[2019] - USD[2010]

# The 'Growth Rate Percent' shows the percentage at which each country is growing. To find this value, 
# I took the differences df I created and divided it by the earliest year of current spending. Then, I multiplied
# this by 100 to convert the decimals to a percent value. 

USD['Growth Rate Percent'] = (USD['Difference']/ USD[2010]) * 100

Part 4 - Future Predictions¶

2020 has brought on the novel challenge that has effected countries globally: SARS-CoV-2 - better known as COVID-19. According to the World Health Organization (https://covid19.who.int/), over one million people have died from this disease as of October 2020. Moreover, over 37 million individuals have been confirmed with having been infected with this virus. Each country has dealt with this novel disease drastically differently. I anticipate that 2020's GDP trends will change drastically globally.

While that data has not been made available, I thought it would be interesting to see if/how countries had changed their military spending in light of another global epidemic. Globally, we have not seen a disease quite like COVID-19 where countries were forced to go into lockdown. However, I thought it would be interesting to take a look at other how these 10 countries I used in this case study to see how the 1968-69 Influenza Outbreak affected military spending. According to the US National Library of Medicine (ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6447676/), the 68-69 strand of the flu saw somewhere between 500,000-2 million deaths globally. I decided to create a new dataframe in order to see the military spending and share of GDP spending in the years right before, during, and after the 68-69 strand of Influenza (1967-1968).

In this prediction, I decided not to include Russia and China because there was no available data for them.

# Defining a new function 'fluChart' in order to create a new dataframe.

def fluChart(xls):
    rname = ['USA', 'Germany', 'UK', 'France', 'Italy', 'Iran', 'Israel',
             'Saudi Arabia'] 
    cname = [1967, 1968, 1969, 1970, 1971]
    
    xls = xls.loc[rname, cname]
    return xls

This prediction is limited in many ways. First, the current political climate is not going to be exactly the same in each country. Second, the 1968-1969 influenza strand did not have the same global effect as COVID-19. Third, it would be difficult to confirm whether any changes in spending was directly correlated with this disease. Last, government powers in each country view the differently now than they did back in the late 1960's.

However, I do believe that there is an opportunity for further research in order to see what, if any coorelations, there are with major global events and their effects on GDP spending.
